ğŸ§© SUBSET / SUBSEQUENCE (INCLUDEâ€“EXCLUDE) RECURSION PATTERN
ğŸ§  DEFINITION

This recursion pattern is used when each element in a collection has two independent choices:
ğŸ‘‰ Include it or ğŸ‘‰ Exclude it from the current result.

It explores all possible combinations (or subsequences) of the input â€” forming a recursion tree of size 2â¿.
Common in problems like Subsets, Subsequences, Combination Sum, and Target Sum.

ğŸ•’ WHEN TO USE

Use this pattern when:

You need to generate all possible combinations or selections of elements.

The problem involves "include or exclude" type decisions for each element.

The question mentions â€œfind all subsetsâ€, â€œprint all subsequencesâ€, â€œall possible waysâ€, â€œcombinationsâ€, or â€œpower set.â€

ğŸ’¬ HOW IT USUALLY APPEARS IN QUESTIONS

Youâ€™ll often see phrases like:

â€œGenerate all possible subsets/subsequences.â€

â€œFind all combinations that sum up to a target.â€

â€œPrint all possible binary strings of length n.â€

â€œReturn all unique combinations of elements.â€

Whenever you see such â€œall possibleâ€ or â€œevery combinationâ€ wording â†’ think INCLUDEâ€“EXCLUDE RECURSION.

ğŸ§  THINKING PROCESS

Whenever you see a problem like

"Find all subsets", "Print all subsequences", or "Generate all combinations",

ask yourself:

For each element â€” can I either take it or skip it?

Do I need all possible results (not just one)?

âœ… If yes â†’ this is an INCLUDEâ€“EXCLUDE recursion problem.

Each element acts as a decision point with two options:

Include â†’ move forward keeping the element.

Exclude â†’ move forward without it.

This naturally forms a binary recursion tree â†’ total 
2N
 outcomes.

âš™ï¸ BASIC TEMPLATE (THINKING FORM)
def solve(idx, arr, current):
    # 1ï¸âƒ£ BASE CASE
    if idx == len(arr):
        process(current)      # print, append, or evaluate
        return

    # 2ï¸âƒ£ CHOICE 1 â€” INCLUDE arr[idx]
    current.append(arr[idx])
    solve(idx + 1, arr, current)
    current.pop()             # backtrack (undo include)

    # 3ï¸âƒ£ CHOICE 2 â€” EXCLUDE arr[idx]
    solve(idx + 1, arr, current)

ğŸ§  KEY THINKING STEPS
STEP	QUESTION	ACTION
1ï¸âƒ£	Whatâ€™s the smallest problem?	When idx == len(arr) (all elements processed)
2ï¸âƒ£	Whatâ€™s the decision per element?	Include or exclude
3ï¸âƒ£	Whatâ€™s the recursive relation?	f(i) = f(i+1 include) + f(i+1 exclude)
4ï¸âƒ£	What to do with partial results?	Store, print, or count subsets
5ï¸âƒ£	Is backtracking needed?	Yes â€” undo include before next call

ğŸ” VARIATIONS OF THIS PATTERN
VARIATION	DESCRIPTION	EXAMPLE PROBLEMS
SUBSETS / POWER SET	Generate all subsets of an array	Subsets (Leetcode 78)
SUBSEQUENCES OF A STRING	Include or exclude each character	Print all subsequences
COMBINATION SUM	Choose or skip numbers with repetition	Combination Sum (Leetcode 39)
TARGET SUM	Assign + or â€“ to reach a target	Target Sum (Leetcode 494)
LETTER COMBINATIONS	Choose one letter for each digit	Letter Combinations of a Phone Number (Leetcode 17)
BINARY STRINGS	Generate all binary strings of length n	Generate Binary Strings
â±ï¸ COMPLEXITY
METRIC	VALUE
TIME COMPLEXITY	
O(2n)--EVERY ELENEBT HAS 2 CHOICES 
SPACE COMPLEXITY	
O(n) â€“ recursion depth

##PROBLEM LEET CODE 78 -- 
ğŸŒŸ VARIATION EXAMPLE â€” LEETCODE 78: SUBSETS
ğŸ§® PROBLEM STATEMENT

Given an integer array nums of unique elements, return all possible subsets (the power set).

The solution set must not contain duplicate subsets.
Return the solution in any order.

ğŸ“¥ INPUT
nums = [1, 2, 3]

ğŸ“¤ OUTPUT
[[], [1], [2], [1, 2], [3], [1, 3], [2, 3], [1, 2, 3]]

âš™ï¸ CONSTRAINTS
1 <= nums.length <= 10
-10 <= nums[i] <= 10
All the numbers of nums are unique.

ğŸ§© PATTERN USED
##POINT TO REMEMBER 
SUBSET / SUBSEQUENCE (INCLUDEâ€“EXCLUDE) RECURSION PATTERN -- â€œFor Subsets and Subsequences, we need to use Includeâ€“Exclude every time, whether it is a string or an array. No problem.â€ 

ğŸ’¡ THINKING PROCESS

For each element, we have two choices:
1ï¸âƒ£ Include the element in the current subset
2ï¸âƒ£ Exclude the element and move on

Continue until we process all elements.

When idx == len(nums) â†’ we have formed one subset.

This explores all 
2 n
 subsets.

ğŸ’» SOLUTION CODE (PYTHON)
class Solution(object):
    def subsets(self, nums):
        """
        :type nums: List[int]
        :rtype: List[List[int]]
        """
        res = []
        c = []
        return self.main(0, nums, c, res)

    def main(self, idx, nums, c, res):
        # BASE CASE: all elements processed
        if idx >= len(nums):
            res.append(c[:])
            return

        # INCLUDE current element
        c.append(nums[idx])
        self.main(idx + 1, nums, c, res)

        # BACKTRACK (UNDO include)
        c.pop()

        # EXCLUDE current element
        self.main(idx + 1, nums, c, res)

        return res

ğŸ§  DRY RUN EXAMPLE

Input â†’ nums = [1, 2]

main(0, [])
â”œâ”€â”€ include 1 â†’ main(1, [1])
â”‚     â”œâ”€â”€ include 2 â†’ main(2, [1,2]) â†’ store [1,2]
â”‚     â””â”€â”€ exclude 2 â†’ main(2, [1])   â†’ store [1]
â””â”€â”€ exclude 1 â†’ main(1, [])
      â”œâ”€â”€ include 2 â†’ main(2, [2])   â†’ store [2]
      â””â”€â”€ exclude 2 â†’ main(2, [])    â†’ store []


âœ… Output â†’ [[], [1], [2], [1,2]]

PROCESS -- '
                               []
                 /                              \
           Take 1                              Skip 1
           [1]                                  []
        /            \                      /           \
   Take 2          Skip 2             Take 2         Skip 2
   [1,2]            [1]                [2]             []
   /    \           /   \              /   \           /   \
T3   S3        T3   S3         T3   S3        T3   S3
â†“      â†“          â†“      â†“          â†“      â†“          â†“      â†“
[1,2,3] [1,2] [1,3] [1] [2,3] [2] [3] []

